  "text": "Formation of microtubules ex vivo was assessed by allowing for polymerization of purified bovine tubulin (at a concentration of 2 mg/ml) employing a turbidity assay in 96-well plate format (HTS-Tubulin Polymerization Assay Kit; Cytoskeleton, Denver, CO, USA). Initial studies were conducted to confirm the sensitivity of the bovine brain tubulin polymerization assay to the inhibitory effects of a known polymerization inhibitor, the vinca alkaloid vincristine sulfate, derived from Catharanthus roseus. Vincristine sulfate binds to ab-tubulin dimers to prevent formation of microtubules, thus leading to mitotic arrest and apoptosis (for review, see [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Previous work has demonstrated the sensitivity of this assay to enhancement of microtubule formation with paclitaxel, which is an antineoplastic agent that promotes tubulin polymerization [CITATION_3] . Polymerization of purified bovine brain tubulin was assessed both in the presence and absence of vincristine sulfate (0.1-10 lM; Sigma-Aldrich, St. Louis, MO). Absorption at 340 nm was measured every 5 min for 45 min using a Beckman-Coulter DTX 880 Multimodal Detector plate reader (Beckman-Coulter, Fullerton, CA, USA). The kinetic assay was terminated at 45 min, as microtubule polymerization has been observed to plateau and remain stable at all timepoints thereafter [CITATION_4] . General tubulin buffer (G-PEM; Cytoskeleton) was used as a control measure of background absorbance.",
